{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01SFQLuCspn6NBnkn9hujEE9","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01MTo3cUdkNfcu2pTzBrecTg","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"A plugin whose manifest is missing a required field is rejected before any code from that plugin is executed.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure boundary is the sequence of validation → loading. A mock filesystem/require would hide if real code calls require() before validation. Must use real filesystem + actual Node.js require() to verify that module code never executes when manifest is invalid. The critical test: create a plugin with an invalid manifest and an entry module that throws if required, verify the loader rejects the manifest and the module is never loaded.","test_description":"Create a plugin directory with a manifest missing a required field. Include an entry module that throws an error if executed. Attempt to load the plugin configuration. Assert: (1) loader rejects with a manifest validation error, (2) the entry module was never required/executed (no error from module code). This requires real filesystem reads and actual Node.js require() mechanics.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Test requires real filesystem + real require() to verify the ordering invariant that validation occurs before module loading. Could not reliably verify this with mocked file I/O.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.85,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When plugin A declares a dependency on plugin B, plugin B's onLoad hook is called before plugin A's.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Dependency topological sorting could be Unit-tested in isolation (algorithm only). However, the actual behavior is about hook execution order. The failure is if hooks run out of order despite correct dependency declaration. Testing the real failure requires setting up real manifests with dependencies, loading them, and verifying hook invocation order. This coordination of multiple plugins, dependencies, and hook execution is Integration-level.","test_description":"Create two plugin directories with manifest files where Plugin A explicitly depends on Plugin B. Both export onLoad hooks (real or with call-tracking mocks). Load the plugin system. Assert that Plugin B's onLoad hook is invoked before Plugin A's onLoad hook. Use call-order tracking to verify the sequence.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Test requires real manifest setup with dependencies and actual hook execution (not just ordering of plugin names). This correctly tests the behavior as stated.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When two plugins each declare a dependency on the other, the loader reports the cycle and loads neither.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Cycle detection as a pure algorithm is Unit-testable. However, the complete behavior includes 'loads neither'—this means no plugin code executes and no onLoad hook runs. The failure is at the orchestration level: does the loader actually prevent loading of cyclic plugins? Testing this requires real manifests with circular dependencies and verification that neither plugin's onLoad is invoked. This is Integration-level.","test_description":"Create two plugin directories with manifests where Plugin A depends on B and Plugin B depends on A. Attempt to load the plugin configuration. Assert: (1) loader detects and reports a cycle error, (2) neither plugin's onLoad hook is called (verified via mock call tracking or by confirming no state changes from either plugin).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Test verifies both cycle detection and non-loading of cyclic plugins, requiring real manifest setup and hook execution tracking. This matches the full behavior statement.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"A plugin's onLoad hook is only invoked after the plugin's entry module has been imported and executed.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is fundamentally about the sequencing of Node.js module loading. The failure is if onLoad is called before require() completes. Mocked require() cannot catch real out-of-order execution in the actual loader code. Must use real JavaScript files and actual require() semantics. The test: create an entry module that sets a flag, verify the flag is set before onLoad executes.","test_description":"Create a plugin entry module (real JavaScript file) that exports a flag set to true on module load (e.g., module.exports.loaded = true). Create a manifest with an onLoad hook. Load the plugin. Assert that the entry module was successfully required (flag is set/exported) before the onLoad hook is invoked. This requires actual file I/O and Node.js require() behavior.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Test requires real JavaScript file execution and actual require() behavior. A mock require() would not reliably catch if the loader calls onLoad before module loading in real code.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.8,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When a plugin throws an error during its onLoad hook, the loader continues initializing the remaining plugins that do not depend on it.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure is in cascading error handling: when one plugin fails, dependents should not load, but independent plugins should continue. Testing requires multiple real plugins with declared dependencies, real hook execution (with error simulation), and verification of load outcomes for each plugin. This coordination is Integration-level. Unit testing error handling in isolation would miss the dependency-aware cascading behavior.","test_description":"Create three plugins: Plugin A (hook throws error), Plugin B (depends on A), Plugin C (no dependency on A). Load the plugin configuration with A's onLoad throwing an error. Assert: (1) loader catches error and continues without crashing, (2) A's onLoad was attempted and threw, (3) B's onLoad is not called (because A failed), (4) C's onLoad is called normally. Verify via hook tracking and plugin state.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Test requires real manifests with dependencies, hook execution with error injection, and verification of cascading behavior. This correctly tests the full behavior of error resilience and dependency-aware loading.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13399,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13399},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c24cdcbe-926e-4748-8170-95371f5d4f4d","uuid":"17056570-a97b-4d92-baf1-eee8cc8390ff"}
